			</history><permissions><copyright-statement hwp:id="copyright-statement-1">© 2021, Posted by Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory</copyright-statement><copyright-year>2021</copyright-year><license license-type="creative-commons" xlink:href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/" hwp:id="license-1"><p hwp:id="p-1">This pre-print is available under a Creative Commons License (Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International), CC BY-NC 4.0, as described at <ext-link l:rel="related" l:ref-type="uri" l:ref="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/" ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/" hwp:id="ext-link-1">http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/</ext-link></p></license></permissions><self-uri l:ref="forthcoming:yes" c:role="http://schema.highwire.org/variant/abstract" xlink:role="abstract" content-type="xhtml+xml" hwp:variant="yes"/><self-uri l:ref="forthcoming:yes" c:role="http://schema.highwire.org/variant/change-list" xlink:role="change-list" content-type="xhtml+xml" hwp:variant="yes"/><self-uri l:ref="forthcoming:yes" c:role="http://schema.highwire.org/variant/full-text" xlink:href="file:/content/biorxiv/vol0/issue2021/pdf/720912v4.pdf" hwp:variant="yes" content-type="pdf" xlink:role="full-text"/><self-uri l:ref="forthcoming:yes" c:role="http://schema.highwire.org/variant/source" xlink:role="source" content-type="xml" xlink:show="none" hwp:variant="yes"/><self-uri l:ref="forthcoming:yes" c:role="http://schema.highwire.org/variant/original" xlink:role="original" content-type="xml" xlink:show="none" hwp:variant="yes" xlink:href="720912.xml"/><self-uri content-type="abstract" xlink:href="file:/content/biorxiv/vol0/issue2021/abstracts/720912v4/720912v4.htslp"/><abstract hwp:id="abstract-1"><p hwp:id="p-2">The leaf veins bundle sheath cells (BSCs) constitute a selective barrier to water and solutes entering the mesophyll and play a major role in regulating the leaf radial hydraulic conductance (K<sub>leaf</sub>). BSCs′ plasma membrane H<sup>+</sup>-ATPase, AHA2, increases K<sub>leaf</sub> by acidifying the xylem sap. We hypothesized, based on the expression of PHOT1 and PHOT2 in Arabidopsis BSCs and on the known blue-light (BL)-induced increase of K<sub>leaf</sub>, that similar to the guard cells BL signal transduction pathway, BL perception by the BSCs′ phots activates its K<sub>leaf</sub> and upregulate Kleaf. Indeed, under BL, the K<sub>leaf</sub> of the knockout mutant lines <italic toggle="yes">phot1-5</italic>, p<italic toggle="yes">hot2-1</italic>, <italic toggle="yes">phot1-5phot2-1</italic>, and <italic toggle="yes">aha2-4</italic> was lower than that of the WT. BSC-only-directed complementation of <italic toggle="yes">phot1-5</italic> or <italic toggle="yes">aha2-4</italic> by PHOT1 and AHA2, respectively, restored the BL-induced increase in Kleaf. BSC-specific silencing of PHOT1 or PHOT2 prevented such K<sub>leaf</sub> increase, and we replicated this in WT plants with a xylem-fed kinase inhibitor (tyrphostin 9). In the PHOT1-complemented <italic toggle="yes">phot1-5</italic>, as in WT, but unlike in <italic toggle="yes">phot1-5</italic>, white light acidified the xylem sap (relative to darkness). These results, supported by assays of BSC protoplasts′ water permeability, hyperpolarization and cytosolic pH, highlight the BSCs′ role in the BL-K<sub>leaf</sub> link as mediators that regulate the xylem-to-mesophyll water flux.</p></abstract><custom-meta-wrap><custom-meta hwp:id="custom-meta-1"><meta-name>special-property</meta-name><meta-value>contains-inline-supplementary-material</meta-value></custom-meta></custom-meta-wrap><custom-meta-wrap>
